reviewText: Filmed inside a beautiful log house in Tennessee. This one is sort of a Homecoming video for all the Gaither singers. It includes The Martins, Booth Brothers,The Isaacs, Guy Penrod, David Phelps, Mark Lowry, Michael English, Wes Hampton, Ronnie Milsap, Dallas Holm and many others. Everyone is expressing thankfulness for their blessings. It even includes a big Thanksgiving dinner where a lot of the Gaither friends are seated at a beautiful table full of food. It's somewhat of a tear-jerker. Michael bares his sole regarding his temporary set backs, and others reminisce about past blessings. Beautiful beautiful singing. I love this video. It speaks to the everyday trials and troubles that make up life for everyone. This is just such a loving and "supporting each other" group that it just makes me feel good to see it.
summary: Filmed inside a beautiful log house in Tennessee

reviewText: Hmm.  Some of this recording is just so good, but not all of it. I would trade it for anything. Wes Hampton sang so from his heart, as did Mike and David as they accompanied him in "He is Here."  A great song, and never sung better. Buddy Greene did a number which version should be a classic -classic "Hard Times Come Again No More." Michael Sykes sang a very simple message: "I love my friends." It brought some tears. Guy Penrod sang his "Breathe Deep," to which most of us could relate. Jason Crabb add his own touch of beauty. That gruff voice is so tender and easy to hear on this recording. Gene McDonald pays tribute with "Thanks to Calvary I Don't Live Here Anymore." He really sounds good on this. Karen Peck sweetly sung the lead in "I Want to Thank You. Ronnie Milsap sang and played. A thirteen year-old Logan Smith belts out Thank You Lord for your Blessings" in a way that makes you want to sing with him. I was a bit disappointed in The Bush Brothers and The Martins. Usually, I very much enjoy both these groups, but wow! The remainder were enjoyable, but I have given you my opinion for whatever it is worth.In short, the good numbers are outstanding, and the ones I did not care for is just my opinion.  You might like them just fine.Mickey Thorne
